Good — "self-contained enough to replay the PR" is the right design constraint. Let me work through each entity with specific fields.

The core tension in the structure is that threads *span* rounds but comments *belong to* rounds. Let me make that explicit.

**Top-level document — one per PR:**

```
PRExport {
  // === Identity ===
  repo_owner          string
  repo_name           string
  repo_primary_language string
  pr_number           int
  pr_url              string

  // === PR metadata (immutable once opened) ===
  pr {
    title             string
    body              string   // markdown
    author            string
    branch_head       string   // e.g. "fix/pool-cleanup"
    branch_base       string   // e.g. "main"
    base_sha          string   // merge-base commit
    labels            []string
    created_at        timestamp
    merged_at         timestamp (nullable)
    closed_at         timestamp (nullable)
    merge_commit_sha  string (nullable)

    // Scope — what the PR touches overall (at merge/close)
    final_files_changed  int
    final_additions      int
    final_deletions      int
  }

  // === Participants ===
  user {
    login             string
    role              enum(author | reviewer | both)
    // "both" for cases where you review your own 
    // or co-author and also review
  }

  participants[] {
    login             string
    role              enum(author | reviewer | commenter)
    association       string   // OWNER, MEMBER, CONTRIBUTOR, etc.
  }

  // === Snapshots ===
  // Keyed by commit SHA. Every SHA referenced anywhere
  // in the export has an entry here.
  // This is the "fact table" for file contents.
  snapshots {
    [sha: string]: Snapshot
  }

  // === Rounds ===
  rounds[]            Round    // ordered chronologically

  // === Threads ===
  threads[]           Thread   // one per conversation chain

  // === Push timeline ===
  // Everything that happened between rounds,
  // for replay fidelity
  pushes[]            Push     // ordered chronologically
}
```

**Snapshot — the world at a commit:**

```
Snapshot {
  sha                 string
  timestamp           timestamp  // commit timestamp

  // Every file that is part of the PR at this point
  // (i.e., differs from base)
  files[] {
    path              string
    language          string     // inferred from extension
    status            enum(added | modified | deleted | renamed)
    previous_path     string (nullable)  // for renames
    content           string (nullable)  // null if deleted
    content_encoding  enum(utf8 | base64) // for binary detection
    size_bytes        int
  }

  // Unchanged files that provide context.
  // Same package/directory as changed files.
  // e.g. if you changed pool.go, include pool_test.go,
  // types.go from the same package even if untouched.
  context_files[] {
    path              string
    language          string
    content           string
    reason            string  // "same_package" | "same_directory" | "imported_by"
  }

  // Precomputed diffs for convenience
  diff_from_base {
    raw_patch         string   // unified diff, full PR
    per_file[] {
      path            string
      previous_path   string (nullable)
      status          enum(added | modified | deleted | renamed)
      patch           string   // unified diff for this file
      additions       int
      deletions       int
    }
  }

  // Diff from the PREVIOUS round's snapshot (null for first round)
  diff_from_previous_snapshot {
    previous_sha      string
    raw_patch         string
    per_file[]        // same structure as above
  }
}
```

**Round — one review session:**

```
Round {
  round_number        int       // 1-indexed, chronological
  snapshot_sha        string    // -> snapshots[sha]
  submitted_at        timestamp

  // The formal review, if one was submitted
  review {                      // nullable — null for loose comments
    review_id         string
    state             enum(APPROVED | CHANGES_REQUESTED | COMMENTED | DISMISSED)
    body              string    // the top-level review message
  }

  // All comments you placed in this round,
  // in the order they appear in the diff (file order, then position)
  comments[]          CommentRef {
    thread_id         string    // -> threads[].thread_id
    comment_id        string    // unique comment id
  }

  // What happened AFTER this round, before the next
  // (null for the last round)
  gap_to_next {
    duration          duration  // wall time to next round
    pushes            []string  // -> pushes[].sha, ordered
    developer_replies []CommentInThread  // replies to your comments
                                        // before your next round
  }
}
```

**Thread — a conversation anchored to a code location:**

This is the key structural decision. A thread is the *full lifecycle* of a single concern, spanning rounds.

```
Thread {
  thread_id           string

  // Where this thread is anchored
  anchor {
    path              string
    start_line        int (nullable)  // for multi-line comments
    end_line          int
    side              enum(LEFT | RIGHT)  // old vs new in diff
    original_sha      string   // the SHA when thread was created
  }

  // The diff hunk AT THE TIME the thread was started
  // (this is what you were looking at when you wrote
  // the first comment)
  original_diff_hunk  string

  // Resolution
  is_resolved         bool
  resolved_by         string (nullable)  // login
  resolution_type     enum(              // inferred, not from API
    addressed          // code was changed to match feedback
    | deferred         // explicitly punted ("follow-up PR")
    | conceded         // reviewer accepted author's approach
    | abandoned        // thread went stale, PR merged anyway
    | null             // can't determine
  )

  // Whether the code location has gone stale
  // (code changed under this thread)
  is_outdated         bool

  // The full conversation, chronologically
  exchanges[] {
    comment_id        string
    round_number      int (nullable)  // which of YOUR rounds 
                                      // this belongs to.
                                      // null for other people's
                                      // standalone replies
    author            string
    is_you            bool
    body              string          // markdown
    created_at        timestamp

    // The diff hunk as it appeared at THIS comment's time
    // (may differ from original_diff_hunk if code was
    // pushed between comments)
    diff_hunk_at_time string
    commit_sha        string          // what SHA this comment
                                      // was placed against

    // Was this comment outdated by the time the PR merged?
    is_outdated       bool

    // Reactions (lightweight signal)
    reactions {
      thumbs_up       int
      thumbs_down     int
      laugh           int
      // etc.
    }
  }
}
```

**Push — a commit event between rounds:**

```
Push {
  sha                 string
  parent_sha          string
  message             string
  author              string
  timestamp           timestamp
  is_force_push       bool     // detected by parent chain break

  // Which round this push falls after
  after_round         int (nullable)  // null if before first review
}
```

**A few design notes:**

The `snapshots` map is intentionally denormalized. The same file content might appear in multiple snapshots unchanged — that's fine. It means any consumer can grab a snapshot SHA and get the complete picture without cross-referencing. For a visualization tool, being able to say "show me the world at round 3" with a single key lookup is worth the storage.

The `resolution_type` on threads is the one field that requires inference rather than raw API data. I'd suggest exporting it as `null` in v1 and letting the analysis layer fill it in later — unless you want to apply simple heuristics during export (like: if the thread's anchor file was modified in the inter-round diff and the thread was resolved, call it `addressed`).

The `context_files` in snapshots is the most expensive part API-wise. For Go repos, "same package" is a natural boundary — all `.go` files in the same directory. Worth scoping this carefully to avoid blowing up API rate limits on large repos.

Does this structure feel right for replay fidelity? The main thing I'm unsure about is whether you'd want the snapshot files stored inline in the JSON or as separate files on disk with the JSON holding paths.

You're right — I was projecting intent onto threads that the data simply doesn't support. The `resolution_type` inference, the `resolved_by` semantics — that's all storytelling on top of messy reality. The export should capture exactly what GitHub knows, nothing more.

A thread is really just: an anchor point in code, and a list of comments that GitHub grouped together. That's it.

```
Thread {
  thread_id           string

  // Where GitHub anchored this conversation
  anchor {
    path              string
    line              int (nullable)
    start_line        int (nullable)  // multi-line range
    side              enum(LEFT | RIGHT)
    original_commit   string
  }

  // The diff hunk when the first comment was placed
  original_diff_hunk  string

  // What GitHub says about resolution — just the raw state
  is_resolved         bool
  is_outdated         bool

  // The comments, in order. That's all we know.
  comments[] {
    comment_id        string
    author            string
    is_target_user    bool
    body              string
    created_at        timestamp
    updated_at        timestamp (nullable)
    commit_sha        string
    diff_hunk_at_time string
    is_outdated       bool
    in_reply_to_id    string (nullable)
    reactions         map[string]int  // emoji -> count

    // Which round this comment was part of,
    // if it belongs to the target user.
    // null for other people's comments
    // and for target user's non-review comments
    // that weren't part of a formal review submission
    round_number      int (nullable)
  }
}
```

The `round_number` linkage is the one piece of cross-referencing worth keeping — it lets you understand "this comment was part of that batch" without inference. Everything else is just what GitHub returns.

The `resolution_type` enum I had before — `addressed`, `deferred`, `conceded`, `abandoned` — that belongs entirely in the analysis layer. The export just says `is_resolved: true` and lets a future tool figure out why.

Does this feel right for threads? If so, let's talk export format.

Good call. The thread was *born* in a round — that's the meaningful association. Individual comments within it are just the conversation unfolding.

```
Thread {
  thread_id           string

  // Which review round initiated this thread
  round_number        int (nullable)  // null if comment wasn't 
                                       // part of a formal round
                                       // (loose comment, or 
                                       // comment by someone else)

  anchor {
    path              string
    line              int (nullable)
    start_line        int (nullable)
    side              enum(LEFT | RIGHT)
    original_commit   string
  }

  original_diff_hunk  string

  // Raw GitHub state
  is_resolved         bool
  is_outdated         bool

  // Placeholder — null at export time,
  // filled by analysis tooling later
  resolution_type     enum(...) (nullable)

  comments[] {
    comment_id        string
    author            string
    is_target_user    bool
    body              string
    created_at        timestamp
    updated_at        timestamp (nullable)
    commit_sha        string
    diff_hunk_at_time string
    is_outdated       bool
    in_reply_to_id    string (nullable)
    reactions         map[string]int
  }
}
```

Cleaner. The thread knows its round, the comments are just the raw conversation. Ready for export format?
